WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.860 --> 00:00:06.010
&gt;&gt;Presenter: Welcome everyone to Photographers
at Google. My name is Ricardo Lagos. Iím

00:00:06.010 --> 00:00:11.351
a software developer. Itís my distinct pleasure
to introduce you to our special guest, photographer

00:00:11.351 --> 00:00:17.930
Eric Cheng. Ericís award-winning photography
has been published in over 60 magazines and

00:00:17.930 --> 00:00:24.900
books worldwide. He has won contests such
as Natureís Best Magazineís Photo Competition,

00:00:24.900 --> 00:00:29.760
which placed some of his work in the Smithsonian
Natural History Museum.

00:00:29.760 --> 00:00:35.370
Eric is the editor and publisher of wetpixel.com,
the premier online community for underwater

00:00:35.370 --> 00:00:40.890
photographers. Wetpixel provides a forum for
photographers to share their work and to discuss

00:00:40.890 --> 00:00:47.580
ocean-related issues, in turn educating viewers
about the beauty and fragility of the marine

00:00:47.580 --> 00:00:53.690
ecosystem. Ericís work with wetpixel.com
was awarded the prestigious Underwater Imaging

00:00:53.690 --> 00:01:01.070
Website of the Year from the Antibes Festival.
Through Wetpixel expeditions, Eric leads regular

00:01:01.070 --> 00:01:07.560
photography expeditions and workshops around
the world. He has given seminars and lectures

00:01:07.560 --> 00:01:15.600
internationally at events such as TEDx, Boston
Sea Roverís Clinic, DEMA, Digital Shootouts,

00:01:15.600 --> 00:01:20.640
Kona Classic, scuba diving magazine events,
and others.

00:01:20.640 --> 00:01:25.900
Eric is also involved in ocean conservation,
and is technical advisor and photographer

00:01:25.900 --> 00:01:30.520
for the Sea Shepherdsí Conservation Society.
He was head photographer for the Operation

00:01:30.520 --> 00:01:38.490
Musashi, Sea Shepherdsí 2008 and 2009 anti-whaling
campaign in Antarctica, which was featured

00:01:38.490 --> 00:01:43.760
in season two of the hit TV show Whale Wars.
You can find more info about Eric and his

00:01:43.760 --> 00:01:51.759
photography at echeng.com. Eric, thanks for
taking time to come to Google today, and welcome.

00:01:51.759 --> 00:01:52.900
[applause]

00:01:52.900 --> 00:02:00.250
&gt;&gt;Eric Cheng: Thanks so much for having me.
That was a very official bio. Itís funny

00:02:00.250 --> 00:02:04.790
because Ricardo told me that in the version
that he sent out to Google, he said something

00:02:04.790 --> 00:02:09.170
like, ìEric was bumming around for a few
years and took some pictures.î [laughter]

00:02:09.170 --> 00:02:15.670
Both are accurate, and I fully own up to both.
Thanks again for having me. I actually started

00:02:15.670 --> 00:02:23.310
out as a software engineer. Twelve years ago,
or I guess even longer now, I worked in a

00:02:23.310 --> 00:02:29.110
cubicle. I guess cubes are not in anymore.
But I started out in software.

00:02:29.110 --> 00:02:35.959
I discovered photographyóI had discovered
photography earlier than that, but had not

00:02:35.959 --> 00:02:40.090
gone underwater with a camera. So nothing
had ever stuck in the photography realm. It

00:02:40.090 --> 00:02:47.129
was really when I took a camera underwater
that it changed my life. It was the inspiration

00:02:47.129 --> 00:02:53.780
I needed to move my photography beyond something
technical into something that really felt

00:02:53.780 --> 00:02:58.480
like photography. Before, I could take a picture
that was sharp, well-exposed, but it never

00:02:58.480 --> 00:03:02.690
did anything for people. It was missing the
inspiration.

00:03:02.690 --> 00:03:08.190
It very quickly changed my life. I worked
as a photographer and publisher for about

00:03:08.190 --> 00:03:14.959
ten years before coming back into industry.
Now Iím at Lytro. Thereís a big Lytro contingent

00:03:14.959 --> 00:03:19.940
over here, on the right side.
I want to talk a little bit aboutójust a

00:03:19.940 --> 00:03:24.129
little bit about the gear and technique involved
in photography, but mostly tell stories of--

00:03:24.129 --> 00:03:31.310
underwater photography, but mostly tell stories
about specific shots and locations.

00:03:31.310 --> 00:03:41.130
This is a quick summary of the housing market
out there for cameras. Thereís a huge range.

00:03:41.130 --> 00:03:48.290
You can get OEM plastic housings for point-and-shoot
cameras for $150, $180. But in the high ends,

00:03:48.290 --> 00:03:54.409
typically, a full rig for SLR aluminum housings,
machined aluminum housings with strobes and

00:03:54.409 --> 00:04:01.311
all the support necessary to hold those strobes
with articulating arms runs $12,000+. So itís

00:04:01.311 --> 00:04:06.970
a huge range.
Up there on theóin the middle is a GoPro

00:04:06.970 --> 00:04:12.260
housing. These are becoming more and more
popular for underwater video and photography,

00:04:12.260 --> 00:04:17.830
although until a few months ago, they didnít
focus underwater without third party housings.

00:04:17.830 --> 00:04:23.580
I have met film crews out in the field who
have discovered that after the shoot, because

00:04:23.580 --> 00:04:27.689
their, in fact, topside videographers taking
cameras underwater, thinking itís very much

00:04:27.689 --> 00:04:33.479
the same. But it is not.
Whatís happening now, as well, is that these

00:04:33.479 --> 00:04:37.780
mirrorless cameras are becoming more and more
popular underwater. Hereís a little line

00:04:37.780 --> 00:04:44.960
up of Nauticam housings. The Sony NEX series
is pretty popular. The NEX 7 in particular

00:04:44.960 --> 00:04:50.719
is really interesting because you can put
magnified obstacle viewfinders to look at

00:04:50.719 --> 00:05:00.190
their very large electronic viewfinder underwater.
This Olympus OMDEM5, easy to remember model

00:05:00.190 --> 00:05:05.490
name, is also really popular. People have
been getting great results with them. So things

00:05:05.490 --> 00:05:12.080
are changing underwater. Typically, a little
bit behind what happens on land.

00:05:12.080 --> 00:05:18.180
This is a very old picture of me in the water.
This is from 2003, with my second SLR rig.

00:05:18.180 --> 00:05:24.949
It was a Canon D60. Sea and Sea Housing. But
pretty much the anatomy of an underwater rig

00:05:24.949 --> 00:05:31.750
has not changed. You have some kind of housing,
a very large dome port for wide angle, for

00:05:31.750 --> 00:05:38.160
the optics thatófor clear, sharp wide angle
shots underwater. Some kind of lighting, so

00:05:38.160 --> 00:05:45.560
in this case, two Ico Light strobes, and articulating
arms. [pause]

00:05:45.560 --> 00:05:49.469
This is a shot thatís a little bit more recent.
Again, the cameras have not changed that much

00:05:49.469 --> 00:05:54.569
in the professional underwater photography
world, still photography world. This is a

00:05:54.569 --> 00:06:00.439
Seacam housing with a Canon 1DS Mark III.
[pause]

00:06:00.439 --> 00:06:07.819
So one thing that is very specific to underwater
photography is that we basically carry around

00:06:07.819 --> 00:06:14.259
mobile studios. Weíre carrying strobes, articulating
arms, and underwater photography is almost

00:06:14.259 --> 00:06:21.539
completely manual. We shoot manual exposure,
manual strobes. The idea is basically to expose

00:06:21.539 --> 00:06:28.361
to the background and fill the foreground.
Thereís not very much color underwater. Water

00:06:28.361 --> 00:06:33.379
strips out light starting from red all the
way down the spectrum. We need to bring full

00:06:33.379 --> 00:06:39.679
spectrum lighting down to get these colors
to pop.

00:06:39.679 --> 00:06:44.000
This is a picture taken with a setup like
the one you saw on the previous slide. Itís

00:06:44.000 --> 00:06:49.580
a very wide angle shot taken in eastern Indonesia,
in Raja Ampat. Those of you who are divers

00:06:49.580 --> 00:06:56.929
will recognize Raja Ampat as being the place
where the reefs are the best. Itís an incredible

00:06:56.929 --> 00:07:04.939
location. Itís incredibly diverse. In fact,
if you go underwater and count fish for a

00:07:04.939 --> 00:07:10.740
fixed amount of time, which is how they measure
diversity, this area has the highest diversity

00:07:10.740 --> 00:07:16.600
of any area in the world, underwater. Thereís
some theories about why this might be. One

00:07:16.600 --> 00:07:21.179
theory is that during the Ice Age, everything
froze over except for this section, and so

00:07:21.179 --> 00:07:27.559
the fish survived here and then repopulated
around the world.

00:07:27.559 --> 00:07:31.490
Because itís incredibly remote, most of the
diving in places like this are done by Liveabord

00:07:31.490 --> 00:07:37.319
dive vessel. The Liveaboards are usually pretty
nice. This is one that I went on, on the upper

00:07:37.319 --> 00:07:45.759
left. The divingís done by tender.
When I started going here, nobody was there.

00:07:45.759 --> 00:07:50.729
There were maybe two boats out there. Now,
it is incredibly popular, and is managed as

00:07:50.729 --> 00:07:58.539
a national park. But because itís very remote,
and there are dozens of Liveaboards operating

00:07:58.539 --> 00:08:01.429
there, you still donít see very many people
when you go.

00:08:01.429 --> 00:08:08.429
In addition to really nice reefs, thereís
a lot of marine life here. This is a school

00:08:08.429 --> 00:08:15.150
of baitfish over a reef that looks what a
reef looks like if youíre 20 feet away. So

00:08:15.150 --> 00:08:20.340
this is what everything looks like underwater
until you light it. This was really cool.

00:08:20.340 --> 00:08:25.939
These baitfish were actually being hunted
by jacks. You can see the whole school moving

00:08:25.939 --> 00:08:31.779
as one organism. The action is pretty interesting,
but itís hard to get an interesting picture

00:08:31.779 --> 00:08:37.130
from something like this. While itís interesting
to look at, you have to think about how to

00:08:37.130 --> 00:08:44.000
get a shot.
In this little ledge there, or a bunch of

00:08:44.000 --> 00:08:48.040
interesting corals, these are really interesting
corals to see under the water. Theyíre very,

00:08:48.040 --> 00:08:51.620
very shallow, and particularly interesting
because theyíre in a location where you can

00:08:51.620 --> 00:08:56.399
shoot upwards through the surface of the water
and see some trees. So I played around here

00:08:56.399 --> 00:09:03.490
and took some shots, but I felt like something
was missing. So I went back to that location

00:09:03.490 --> 00:09:10.110
and just waited, and I noticed that those
baitfish were moving around a lot on top of

00:09:10.110 --> 00:09:18.180
me. So I just waited. I took a lot of pictures.
Eventually, I got the shot that I wanted,

00:09:18.180 --> 00:09:25.100
which was a shot where the baitfish were above
me, but you could see through the school to

00:09:25.100 --> 00:09:27.241
see some of the surface elements. So this
isó

00:09:27.241 --> 00:09:30.110
&gt;&gt;Male #1: How shallow is it, and is it natural
light?

00:09:30.110 --> 00:09:33.410
&gt;&gt;Cheng: How shallow is it, and is it natural
light? Itís very shallow. Itís like ten

00:09:33.410 --> 00:09:37.931
feet deep. It is natural light in the background,
but strobe-filled in the foreground. This

00:09:37.931 --> 00:09:43.120
is in the shadow of a cliff. So thereís no
light. If you had taken this without, you

00:09:43.120 --> 00:09:47.720
would have gotten just silhouette.
So lighting is really interesting underwater

00:09:47.720 --> 00:09:52.250
because there are a lot of particles floating
around. If you use a flash thatís very close

00:09:52.250 --> 00:09:56.310
to the lens, it lights up all of those particles
between you and your subject. Thatís called

00:09:56.310 --> 00:10:01.319
ìbackscatter.î Even though the visibility
was not that great in the shot that I showed

00:10:01.319 --> 00:10:06.139
before, you donít see very much backscatter.
Thatís because we light things like this.

00:10:06.139 --> 00:10:12.949
This is a picture my friend David Fleetham's
set up. It illustrates how we position strobes.

00:10:12.949 --> 00:10:17.879
Where the fall off lighting intersects is
where you want your subject to be. The reason

00:10:17.879 --> 00:10:21.541
we do that is so that none of the water between
you and the subject is illuminated, so it

00:10:21.541 --> 00:10:22.930
doesnít ruin your shot.

00:10:22.930 --> 00:10:33.740
&gt;&gt;Male #2: In this shot, and in the previous
shots, it wasnít very obvious: are your cameras

00:10:33.740 --> 00:10:34.740
neutrally buoyant?

00:10:34.740 --> 00:10:36.560
&gt;&gt;Cheng: Are cameras neutrally buoyant? They
can be made to be neutrally buoyant.

00:10:36.560 --> 00:10:38.060
&gt;&gt;Male #2: How about your setup?

00:10:38.060 --> 00:10:44.100
&gt;&gt;Cheng: Mine is slightly negative. Historically,
manufacturers have not paid attention to buoyancy,

00:10:44.100 --> 00:10:49.190
and they should. Video housing manufacturers
do pay quite a lot of attention to buoyancy.

00:10:49.190 --> 00:10:55.640
But if itís too heavy, it becomes very difficult
to hold, so we will typically put closed cell

00:10:55.640 --> 00:11:02.129
foam floats on the setup to make it more buoyant
until itís where you like it. If itís totally

00:11:02.129 --> 00:11:07.949
neutral, I find that it also becomes difficult
to use for stills.

00:11:07.949 --> 00:11:12.329
So again, hereís the shot from before. You
can see the strobes are really never pointing

00:11:12.329 --> 00:11:16.939
at the subject. Theyíre always pointing slightly
out so the fall off light is what brushes

00:11:16.939 --> 00:11:20.710
the subject in front of you. Itís a nice
soft light. And, of course, the choice of

00:11:20.710 --> 00:11:26.300
strobe matters. Some strobes have a very hard
edge, and itís hard to use that fall off

00:11:26.300 --> 00:11:31.690
lighting to light your subjects.
So again, the goal is really to expose the

00:11:31.690 --> 00:11:36.230
background and to fill the foreground. You
get these nice colors popping in the front,

00:11:36.230 --> 00:11:41.600
but a nice dark blue in the background. Cameras
do not exposeóTheyíre not designed to expose

00:11:41.600 --> 00:11:45.170
well underwater, so if you just take a camera
underwater and just take a picture in auto

00:11:45.170 --> 00:11:50.060
mode, youíll get a very bright background.
Who knows what youíll get in the foreground.

00:11:50.060 --> 00:11:57.029
We just fill-- use these strobes to fill.
If youíre in the shallows, you can shoot

00:11:57.029 --> 00:12:02.380
a little bitóYou can use white balance. You
donít need to use strobes as much. You can

00:12:02.380 --> 00:12:06.830
use the strobes to fill as much as you can
for these scenes that have subjects that go

00:12:06.830 --> 00:12:13.249
further off. But the strobes that weíre bringing
are actually quite big, but they still donít

00:12:13.249 --> 00:12:18.370
light the reef up for very far. They like
maybe six feet in front of you. We shoot super

00:12:18.370 --> 00:12:23.029
wide. A lot of fisheye.
These reefs are from Raja Ampat, that same

00:12:23.029 --> 00:12:28.100
area. This is one of my favorite shots. Itís
a giant clam in the foreground, reef in the

00:12:28.100 --> 00:12:33.550
background. This school of juvenile convict
fish swimming around. Whatís interesting

00:12:33.550 --> 00:12:39.139
is I had gone there the day before, and the
reef had been dead. Same dive, same location,

00:12:39.139 --> 00:12:43.320
different time of day. And when the current
picked up, all the fish came out. Itís a

00:12:43.320 --> 00:12:51.279
highly dynamic environment. [pause]
This is a shot of a reef called Mikeís Point

00:12:51.279 --> 00:12:58.250
in Raja Ampat. Thereís a ton of current flow
through here. These upwellings that feed the

00:12:58.250 --> 00:13:05.580
coral. This is what that point looks like
from land. It looks like nothing, really,

00:13:05.580 --> 00:13:09.230
but itís ringed by really incredible reefs.
And, in fact, this little island leaves a

00:13:09.230 --> 00:13:13.260
wake because of the current, and was bombed
in World War II because they thought it was

00:13:13.260 --> 00:13:19.731
a boat. [laughter] [pause]
Okay. On the other side of the spectrum, we

00:13:19.731 --> 00:13:24.629
have very, very small things underwater to
photograph. This is the smallest seahorse

00:13:24.629 --> 00:13:30.870
in the world, a pygmy seahorse. Thatís one
of my friendís eyes. So you can see it in

00:13:30.870 --> 00:13:35.350
the upper right hand side of the frame. Tiny,
tiny seahorse. Very hard to see. If youíre

00:13:35.350 --> 00:13:40.399
over 40, you may never see one in your life.
We have a lot of people who take pictures

00:13:40.399 --> 00:13:46.200
where the guide points, and hope itís in
the frame. Thatís not a good way to do it.

00:13:46.200 --> 00:13:50.510
[laughter]
That shot was taken in Papua New Guinea. This

00:13:50.510 --> 00:13:55.309
is an idea of one of the resorts there. Thatís
Lota Wata Island. We used wheelbarrows to

00:13:55.309 --> 00:14:00.740
get our gear around. We hopped on a boat,
went to Rabaul, and the volcano blew while

00:14:00.740 --> 00:14:05.389
we were there, and covered the reef with ash,
which was very interesting, but not great

00:14:05.389 --> 00:14:10.660
for photography.
This is the typical picture people get of

00:14:10.660 --> 00:14:18.150
pygmy seahorses. A macroshot. We typically
use 100 millimeter macrolenses. Sometimes

00:14:18.150 --> 00:14:22.020
with diopters to get even closer. I took a
bunch of these shots. Didnít really like

00:14:22.020 --> 00:14:27.399
any of them. Theyíre hard to shoot because
they donít like you. They donít like divers.

00:14:27.399 --> 00:14:31.430
They donítí like light. So if you get really
close to one and try to take a picture, theyíll

00:14:31.430 --> 00:14:36.709
turn away and youíll get shots of themóof
their backs a lot. This picture took a while

00:14:36.709 --> 00:14:42.740
to get. I asked a friend to take his mask
of underwater, and just sit in front ofóbehind

00:14:42.740 --> 00:14:50.209
this fan. We waited a long time for the pygmy
seahorse to just continue doing its thing,

00:14:50.209 --> 00:14:55.670
until it totally ignored us. Then I was able
to get these shots. So this is that final

00:14:55.670 --> 00:15:00.959
shot.
I like this shot a lot because it shows scale.

00:15:00.959 --> 00:15:04.290
Typically, youíll see a full frame shot of
one of these things, and it looks interesting

00:15:04.290 --> 00:15:13.389
because itís a bizarre animal, but you have
no idea how big it is. [pause]

00:15:13.389 --> 00:15:19.779
This is another one of my favorites. Itís
unusual. Most people think this is a forest

00:15:19.779 --> 00:15:27.529
scene when they see it, but thereís of course
a fish in there. These corals are less than

00:15:27.529 --> 00:15:35.100
a foot tall, so the scale is deceiving. The
equipment that was necessary to get this was

00:15:35.100 --> 00:15:38.689
a little bit unusual. Itís not used very
often.

00:15:38.689 --> 00:15:45.589
This is the camera setup I used for that.
Itís an SLR, a typical SLR rig. But it has

00:15:45.589 --> 00:15:52.550
this very long lens in the front, which is
pseudo endoscopic. So itís a relay lens with

00:15:52.550 --> 00:15:58.199
many, many different elements. I think there
are 18 elements or something. Bad for image

00:15:58.199 --> 00:16:03.269
quality, but great for composition. And so
what happens is you get a fisheye view, a

00:16:03.269 --> 00:16:07.680
very, very wide angle view at the end of the
lens. You can focus all the way up to the

00:16:07.680 --> 00:16:13.629
lens. Very unusual underwater. Normally we
use big dome ports for wide angle optics that

00:16:13.629 --> 00:16:18.340
prevent you from getting very close to your
subject. Shooting wide angle and macro, close

00:16:18.340 --> 00:16:25.059
focus wide angle, is typically very difficult.
We call this the ìinsect eye lens.î I think

00:16:25.059 --> 00:16:29.079
in Japan they call it ìbug eye.î So thatís
where that name came from.

00:16:29.079 --> 00:16:32.879
This is one of the shots that you can get
with it. If you donít know what these are,

00:16:32.879 --> 00:16:37.829
it might seem like a normal shot. But that
hole in the coral is less than a centimeter

00:16:37.829 --> 00:16:43.480
in diameter. And so these are two tiny little
coral hermit crabs shot wide angle from probably

00:16:43.480 --> 00:16:49.200
less than a centimeter away. Then you have
the reef falling off in the background. Pretty

00:16:49.200 --> 00:16:54.059
unusual shots.
Again, these shots were taken in New Guinea.

00:16:54.059 --> 00:16:58.480
But very, very remote New Guinea. These were
taken in a place called the Eastern Fields,

00:16:58.480 --> 00:17:03.110
pretty much halfway between Papua New Guinea
and Australia. Itís about 100 miles from

00:17:03.110 --> 00:17:07.569
Port Moresby, and thereís a very large sunken
volcano thatísóI think itís 400 miles in

00:17:07.569 --> 00:17:13.189
diameter. But it never breaks the surface,
so treacherous for ships. No boats go there.

00:17:13.189 --> 00:17:18.020
Thereís only one dive boat I know that goes
here, and one captain who knows it well. So

00:17:18.020 --> 00:17:21.029
itís pristine.
You can see in this picture here. Itís just

00:17:21.029 --> 00:17:29.430
shallow reefs when youíre above one. Beautiful
water. These are the corals that I was talking

00:17:29.430 --> 00:17:33.380
about. Theyíre very common corals. These
are the kinds of corals you just swim by,

00:17:33.380 --> 00:17:39.390
because theyíre so boring. But you can get
a very different view of these corals with

00:17:39.390 --> 00:17:45.700
this lens. Specifically, you can insert the
lens under the canopy and get shots from inside

00:17:45.700 --> 00:17:48.690
this coral forest, really.

00:17:48.690 --> 00:17:52.541
&gt;&gt;Male #1: So the strobes have to go under
the lens?

00:17:52.541 --> 00:17:55.179
&gt;&gt;Cheng: So the strobesóThe question is about
strobes. The strobe do not go under the lens.

00:17:55.179 --> 00:17:59.720
What Iím doing is putting the strobes on
top of the entireóon top of the corals, and

00:17:59.720 --> 00:18:03.600
looking for holes I canófrom which I can
insert the light.

00:18:03.600 --> 00:18:06.010
&gt;&gt;Male #1: So you have them separated? You
donít have them attached to each other?

00:18:06.010 --> 00:18:09.020
&gt;&gt;Cheng: Yeah, the strobes are attached to
the housing by articulating arms, so we can

00:18:09.020 --> 00:18:17.830
position them wherever we want. Yeah. [pause]
So hereís the final shot. It looks like this

00:18:17.830 --> 00:18:24.091
mossy bank of the left. You can get some other
interesting pictures with this setup. This

00:18:24.091 --> 00:18:29.179
is an Emperor shrimp on a rather large nudibranch.
